---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";

const description =
  "Plain Theory Labs builds engines that measure and grade AI compute infrastructure. ACE ingests scheduler exports and telemetry and produces traceable efficiency scores for policy decisions, procurement, and public reporting.";
---

<BaseLayout title="Plain Theory Labs" description={description}>
  <section class="section prose">
    <h1>Plain Theory Labs</h1>
    <p class="thesis">Plain Theory Labs builds engines that measure and grade AI compute infrastructure.</p>

    <p>
      ACE, our first engine, ingests scheduler exports and telemetry and produces traceable
      efficiency scores that institutions can use for policy decisions, procurement requirements,
      and public reporting.
    </p>

    <p>The standard for sustainable compute does not exist yet. We are building it.</p>

    <hr class="rule" />

    <h2>The problem</h2>

    <p>
      AI compute is scaling faster than anyone can measure its impact. Data centers draw more
      power, consume more water, and strain more grids every year. The tools to monitor this
      exist. The tools to improve it do not.
    </p>

    <p>
      HPC administrators can see utilization. They cannot produce a defensible,
      assumption-explicit efficiency grade that a sustainability office, a procurement committee,
      or a government agency can act on. There is no independent standard for what sustainable
      compute looks like.
    </p>

    <p>That is what Plain Theory Labs builds.</p>

    <hr class="rule" />

    <h2>How we work</h2>

    <p>
      We build engines. Each engine takes real operational data — scheduler logs, telemetry,
      facility metrics — and produces a structured, traceable output with explicit assumptions
      and measurable outcomes. No black boxes. No undisclosed methodology. Every number has a
      source.
    </p>

    <p>
      ACE is engine one. Future engines will address workload scheduling, cooling efficiency,
      carbon intensity, and hardware procurement. Together they form a certification framework
      for AI compute infrastructure.
    </p>

    <hr class="rule" />

    <h2>ACE</h2>

    <p>
      ACE ingests Slurm <code>sacct</code> exports and GPU telemetry, scores per-job efficiency,
      applies safety guardrails, and produces a zero-dependency HTML report with traceable
      recommendations.
    </p>

    <p>
      Validated on the MIT Supercloud HPCA22 dataset. 35,745 jobs. Real scheduler logs and DCGM
      telemetry. Average GPU utilization: 25.7%. Jobs under one minute: 41%. Near-zero GPU
      activity: 33%. The recommendations are specific, the assumptions are disclosed, and the
      safety mode blocks anything we cannot defend.
    </p>

    <p class="inline-links">
      <a href="/ace">ACE Engine &rarr;</a>
    </p>

    <hr class="rule" />

    <h2>Why now</h2>

    <p>
      Communities near data centers are pushing back on water usage, power draw, and grid strain.
      The EU AI Act includes environmental impact provisions. Federal AI infrastructure spending
      is under scrutiny. Institutions that want to get ahead of this need a methodology and a
      grade. Right now neither exists.
    </p>

    <p>Plain Theory Labs is building both.</p>

    <hr class="rule" />

    <p class="inline-links"><a href="/contact">Work with us &rarr;</a></p>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
